        <h2 id="examples">Real optimal posting time examples</h2>

        <h3>1. B2B company — 40% engagement increase by shifting 3 hours</h3>
        <p>A B2B company had been posting LinkedIn content at 8 AM after reading industry benchmarks. After analysing their own LinkedIn Analytics, they found their audience — primarily senior marketing and operations professionals — was most active at 11 AM. Shifting posts to 11 AM generated 40% more engagement on equivalent content, with no change to creative quality or posting frequency.</p>

        <h3>2. Local bakery — 3x engagement by aligning with morning scrolling</h3>
        <p>A bakery initially posted Instagram content at 2 PM, when content was being created. After testing, they found their audience — local professionals — scrolled Instagram during their morning commute and before work. Moving posts to 7:30 AM produced 3x higher engagement. Monthly follower growth increased from 1% to 3.5%.</p>

        <h3>3. Creator account — weekend timing for lifestyle content</h3>
        <p>A lifestyle content creator discovered that professional-advice content performed best Tuesday at 9 AM, while aspirational/travel content performed best Saturday at 10 AM. By segmenting content type by posting day, they increased overall weekly engagement by 55% without creating additional content.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Optimal posting time vs content calendar — how they work together</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
