        <h2 id="best-practices">7 optimal posting time best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start with native analytics, not industry benchmarks.</strong> Your audience's activity pattern is more valuable than a benchmark averaged across millions of different accounts. Check Instagram Insights and LinkedIn Analytics before testing anything else.</li>
          <li><strong>Test with like-for-like content.</strong> To isolate the effect of posting time, compare posts of the same format and topic. Don't test a Reel at 8 AM against a text post at 12 PM — the format variable will overwhelm the time variable.</li>
          <li><strong>Use engagement rate, not raw engagement.</strong> A post reaching 10,000 people with 100 engagements (1%) outperforms one reaching 500 people with 50 engagements (10%). Track the rate to measure algorithm signal strength.</li>
          <li><strong>Test for at least 2–4 weeks per time slot.</strong> Single data points are meaningless. Algorithm variation, day-of-week effects, and seasonal patterns require a minimum of 4–6 posts per time slot to produce reliable data.</li>
          <li><strong>Optimise scheduling, not manual posting.</strong> Publishing manually at a specific time is unreliable. Use a scheduling tool that publishes automatically at the optimal window — especially for accounts posting to multiple time zones.</li>
          <li><strong>Re-test quarterly.</strong> Audience habits shift. Platform algorithms change their distribution logic. A posting time that outperformed in Q1 may not in Q3. Run a brief time-slot test each quarter.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond within the first 30 minutes after posting.</strong> Replying to comments in the post's first hour adds engagement signals that feed the algorithmic distribution test window — extending the reach boost from good timing.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — applying one optimal time across all platforms</div>
          <p>LinkedIn's audience is active during business hours. Instagram's audience is active during personal time. TikTok's is active on breaks and evenings. These are fundamentally different contexts. A single "best time to post" applied across all channels will be wrong for at least two of them.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common posting time mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Using industry benchmarks without testing your audience</strong> — benchmarks are averages, not prescriptions. Your audience may be night-shift workers, stay-at-home parents, or executives — all of whom have very different peak times.</li>
          <li><strong>Posting at content creation time</strong> — when a piece of content is ready is not when it should be published. Schedule it for the optimal window, even if that's 18 hours later.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring time zone distribution</strong> — an audience split across US East and West coasts has a 3-hour peak window gap. Posting at 10 AM ET misses the West Coast morning entirely.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating all days equally</strong> — Monday through Sunday have different engagement profiles on every platform. Tuesday-Thursday consistently outperforms Monday and Friday on most professional networks.</li>
          <li><strong>Posting too frequently at off-peak times</strong> — 5 posts per week at the wrong time produces worse results than 3 posts per week at the right time. Frequency does not compensate for timing.</li>
        </ul>

